## 4. Driver Abort Messages

The driver enforces a small set of invariants. When it aborts, here's how to recover.

### `Working tree dirty. Commit or stash first.`

```bash
git status
git stash push -u -m "before ralph"      # keep changes for later
# or
git add -A && git commit -m "wip"        # commit them
```

### `Detached HEAD. Checkout a branch first.`

Use ref plumbing to avoid prohibited `git checkout`:

```bash
git symbolic-ref HEAD refs/heads/<your-feature-branch>
git read-tree <your-feature-branch>
```

(Or just `git checkout <branch>` from your shell ŌĆö the prohibition is on the *agent*, not on you.)

### `Cannot detect base branch (origin/HEAD, main, master, init.defaultBranch all missing)`

The base branch ref is gone. Recover via reflog:

```bash
# Find the SHA of where the feature branch was created
git reflog --all | grep "Created from"

# Restore the base branch
git update-ref refs/heads/main <sha>

# Optionally pin init.defaultBranch so this can't happen again
git config init.defaultBranch main
```

### `Story flipped to 'passed' but no new commit detected.`

Agent broke the commit-verify invariant ŌĆö they marked a story `passed` without committing. Two cases:

1. **Agent forgot to commit but did the work**: inspect `git status`. If the diff matches the story, manually commit (`git add -A && git commit -m "feat: US-NNN - <title>"`) and re-run.
2. **Agent fabricated the pass**: revert the PRD edit, set the story's `status` back to `todo`, add `notes: previous attempt fabricated pass; please complete real work` and re-run.

### `Invariant violation: more than one story is in_progress.`

Agent broke single-in-progress. Fix manually: open `prd.json`, pick *one* of the `in_progress` stories to keep, set the others back to `todo`. Run again.

### `Sentinel present but stories not all passed`

Agent created `.ralph/.complete` prematurely. Driver auto-cleans the file before exiting; your job is to investigate the unfinished stories, decide if they should be `todo` (retry) or `blocked` (leave aside), and run again.

### `COMMIT REPAIR EXHAUSTED (3 retries)` ŌĆö v1.1 commit-failure handling

When the agent's `git commit` fails (typically: pre-commit hook rejection, lint gate, type error, signing failure), the driver **does not `git reset --hard`**. Instead it:

1. Detects the failure pattern (agent exited non-zero + working tree dirty + HEAD didn't move)
2. Preserves the working tree
3. Writes `.ralph/.commit-failure` (a JSON file with `retry`, `timestamp`, `iteration`)
4. Lets the next iteration's agent attempt repair via `## Commit Repair` in `.ralph/prompt.md`

The agent diagnoses, fixes the root cause, re-runs quality checks, commits, deletes the sentinel, and the loop continues. **Retry budget: 3.** After 3 consecutive failed repairs, driver aborts with `COMMIT REPAIR EXHAUSTED`.

When you see this abort:

```bash
# 1. Inspect what the agent left
cat .ralph/.commit-failure        # see retry count, timestamp, last failed iteration
git status                         # see preserved working tree
git diff                           # see the half-finished work

# 2. Decide one of:

# (a) Fix manually ŌĆö pre-commit hook is misconfigured / blocking unfairly
# Fix the hook, then commit yourself or let agent retry
rm .ralph/.commit-failure
{{RUN_COMMAND}} N                  # agent picks up clean state next iter

# (b) Drop the half-finished work and mark the story blocked
git restore --staged . && git restore .
rm .ralph/.commit-failure
# edit prd.json: flip the in_progress story ŌåÆ status: blocked, add notes
{{RUN_COMMAND}} N

# (c) Salvage what's there as a manual commit, mark story passed
git add -A
git commit -m "feat: US-NNN - <title>" --no-verify  # if hook is the blocker
# edit prd.json: flip status: passed for that story
rm .ralph/.commit-failure
{{RUN_COMMAND}} N
```

**Don't** just delete `.ralph/.commit-failure` and re-run ŌĆö that resets the retry counter without addressing the root cause; the same hook will fail the same way and you'll burn 3 more iterations before another abort.

### `SENTINEL WITH DIRTY TREE` ŌĆö v1.2 step 10g symmetry guard

When `.ralph/.complete` is present and all stories are `passed`, but `git status --porcelain` is non-empty, the driver **refuses** to declare success and exits with code 1 + `EXIT_REASON="SENTINEL WITH DIRTY TREE"`. This catches the corner where the agent commits the final passed-flip and creates `.complete`, then a post-commit tool (formatter, codegen, lint hook) leaves stray edits that aren't part of the committed work.

```bash
# 1. Inspect what's still uncommitted
git status                          # full view
git diff                             # unstaged changes
git diff --staged                    # staged-but-not-committed

# 2. Decide one of:

# (a) Commit the leftover changes (agent missed them but they're real work)
git add -A && git commit -m "chore: post-completion fixups"
# .ralph/.complete was removed by the abort; re-run agent so it sees a clean tree
{{RUN_COMMAND}} N                   # next iter step 10b' will fire ALL STORIES COMPLETE

# (b) Revert tracked-file modifications (post-commit tool noise on tracked files)
git restore --staged . && git restore .
{{RUN_COMMAND}} N                   # same as above

# (b2) Also remove untracked files (post-commit tool created new files, e.g.
# codegen `.d.ts`, build artifacts). `git status --porcelain` flags untracked
# files as dirty too, so option (b) alone is not enough. ŌÜĀ’ĖÅ Data-loss risk:
# `git clean -fd` deletes anything not tracked AND not gitignored. Inspect first:
git status --short                  # untracked files show as "?? path"
git clean -fdn                      # dry-run; print what would be removed
git clean -fd                       # actually remove
{{RUN_COMMAND}} N

# (c) Generated file should be gitignored
# Check why git sees the file as dirty (newly tracked? .gitignore miss?)
# Fix .gitignore or `git rm --cached <file>`, then commit, then re-run.
```

**Don't** just delete the abort message and re-run hoping it goes away ŌĆö driver detects the same dirty state next iter and aborts again.

### `BACKLOG EXHAUSTED (N blocked)` ŌĆö v1.2 backlog-exhausted early exit

When all PRD stories are in terminal state (`passed` Ōł¬ `blocked`) but **at least one is `blocked`**, the driver exits **with code 2** instead of burning iterations spawning agents that have nothing actionable to do. The summary line reads `Final state: BACKLOG EXHAUSTED (N blocked)`. This is **not a failure** ŌĆö exit 2 means "needs human attention", distinct from exit 1 (genuine error) and exit 0 (full success).

The driver also auto-cleans `.ralph/.commit-failure` if present (defensive: prevents a stale repair-retry counter from leaking into the next bootstrap).

When you see this exit:

```bash
# Inspect blocked list (driver already printed it; this is the persistent view):
jq '.userStories[] | select(.status == "blocked") | {id, title, notes}' prd.json

# Decide per blocked story:

# (a) Address the blocker, then unblock:
# edit prd.json: status blocked ŌåÆ todo, optionally append context to notes
{{RUN_COMMAND}} N                  # driver resumes from todo state

# (b) Accept the gap and ship:
# edit prd.json: status blocked ŌåÆ passed (only if you've manually completed the story
# in code AND committed it ŌĆö driver's commit-verify won't catch a manual flip without
# a corresponding new commit, but the gap to "real done" is now your responsibility)
{{RUN_COMMAND}} N                  # driver re-checks; if all passed ŌåÆ ALL STORIES COMPLETE

# (c) Drop the story from PRD entirely:
# remove the entry from prd.json.userStories[]; renumber priorities if needed
{{RUN_COMMAND}} N
```

**Note**: the dirty-tree guard means step 10b' will *not* fire if the working tree has uncommitted changes (e.g., from an in-flight `.commit-failure` repair). The agent will be spawned to handle repair first; backlog-exhausted check fires only on a clean tree.

